Observe the relation of the tense here to the historical present, venit, ‘when he arrives the queen has already assumed her position and taken her place in the midst.’ mediam: for in medio. The queen disposes her person with dignity (composuit) on a sepa- rate couch in the midst —i.e. in the place of honor, having the Carthaginian princes, such as Bitias (1. 738), on one side, and her Trojan guests on 'the other. Virgil supposes the guests to recline at the banquet, though this practice does not seem to have been introduced until long after the heroic age.
